Why America must not re-elect President Bush
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I was cursed by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 with a campaign program that promised a policy of "modesty" in foreign affairs.
If he is re-elected, this is a vote for the Bush doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq -, and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policies at the ballot boxes, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
They have, however, also led to the suspension of the indispensable critical process for democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of the pending problems.
Bush silenced criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
Indeed, Bush played Osama bin Laden directly into his hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America occurred all over the world.
These have given way to widespread bitterness.
Clearly more people than on September 11 are today willing to risk their lives to kill Americans.
Bush often claims that terrorists hate Americans for who they are - a freedom-loving people - not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Just as little was the torture of detainees at the Abu Ghraib prison the work of a few "bad apples".
It was part of a system for dealing with detainees set up by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq pay the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands with him by addressing the fears caused by the September 11 attacks.
In times of danger, people flock to their flag, and Bush has exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign is based on the assumption that people are ultimately not interested in the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something must be wrong with America if we fall for it.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein was involved in September 11, even though the September 11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly concluded that no such connection existed.
One would like to scream: "Wake up, America.
Don't you realize that we are being led by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false assumptions from the beginning to the end - if it ever ended.
It was a war of choice, not necessity.
Much more, America went to war under a pretext: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to free Iraq.
But one cannot impose democracy by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad that they are rid of him.
America, however, had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we stood idly by as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If it had really been about the Iraqi people, we would have had to deploy a larger number of troops for the occupation.
We would have had to protect not only the oil ministry, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: where American troops encountered resistance, they used methods - such as breaking into private homes and mistreating detainees - that pushed the population around and humiliated them, thereby causing bitterness and anger.
The retreats and missteps of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to reestablish it.
First, the US tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought its help.
When the uprisings could no longer be managed, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protegé known as a "strong man" - a far from democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq remains bleak.
A large part of the western part of the country was left to the insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly diminishing.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also caused immense damage to America, weakened its military strength, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an image of overwhelming strength.
Not anymore.
Afghanistan is slipping from control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed vigor.
One can criticize the Bush Administration on many other political issues, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The cost of the war has so far reached nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush taunted John Kerry, telling him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But it will not be easy for him either, because America is stuck in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats have urgently warned Bush not to invade Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process, arguing that any criticism of the commanding officer endangers the US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should pause and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection would raise another question: Is Bush's cowboy attitude qualified to keep him as America's top commander?
